.SH NAME
hsh - a simple command interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
hsh [FILENAME]
.SH DESCRIPTION
hsh executes commands read from standard input or from a file.  It is a POSIX-compliant shell, meaning that it conforms to the IEEE Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) standard for shell behavior.

hsh has several built-in commands, including the following:

alias: Define or print command aliases.
cd: Change the current working directory.
command: Run a command without expanding aliases.
env: Print the environment variables.
eval: Evaluate an expression.
exec: Replace the current shell process with a new process.
exit: Exit the shell.
export: Export an environment variable.
hash: Display or modify the command hash table.
help: Display help information for a command.
history: Print the command history.
pwd: Print the current working directory.
read: Read a line from standard input.
set: Set the value of a variable.
unalias: Remove a command alias.
unset: Unset a variable.

hsh also supports several shell features, including:

Command substitution: Execute a command and substitute its output into another command.
Variable substitution: Expand shell variables in commands.
Quoting: Protect characters from special interpretation.

.SH EXAMPLES
The following are some examples of how to use hsh:

Start hsh
hsh

List the contents of the current directory
ls

Change to the home directory
cd ~

Print the environment variables
env

Define an alias
alias ll='ls -l'

Run the alias
ll

Exit hsh
exit


.SH SEE ALSO
sh(1), bash(1), csh(1), dash(1)

